          "body": "The verb *gennao* (to be born) appears eight times in vv. 3-8, every instance in the passive voice. The grammatical agent is therefore not the person being born but the One doing the birthing — God by His Spirit (3:5-8). Three things must be said. First, the birth is *from above* (*anothen*, 3:3, 7) — its source is heaven, not human effort. Second, it is *of water and the Spirit* (3:5) — best read as a hendiadys for the cleansing-and-renewing work of the Spirit prophesied in Ezekiel 36:25-27 (*I will sprinkle clean water on you... and I will put My Spirit within you*), which Nicodemus as *the teacher of Israel* should have recognized (3:10). Third, it is *sovereign* — like the wind, the Spirit's regenerating work blows where He wills (3:8). The new birth is monergistic: God acts, and the person is born. Orthodox commentators in the Reformed tradition (Calvin, Carson) and the classical Arminian tradition (Wesley) both affirm regeneration is God's work, though they differ on its relationship to faith (cause-of vs. concurrent-with). Both readings preserve the chapter's bedrock: the new birth is something done *to* you, not *by* you."
