        "title": "The ministries overlap — bridge to the Baptist's final witness",
        "range": "3:22-26",
        "excerpt": "After these things Jesus and His disciples came into the land of Judea, and there He was spending time with them and baptizing.",
        "body": "John shifts scenes deliberately. The Nicodemus dialogue concluded; Jesus moves from Jerusalem into the Judean countryside, where He and His disciples are baptizing — the only place in the NT where Jesus is described as conducting a baptizing ministry (John clarifies at 4:2 that Jesus Himself did not baptize, His disciples did). Simultaneously, John the Baptist is operating *in Aenon near Salim, because there was much water there* (3:23). The geographical realism — the abundance of water at a specific named location — is eyewitness detail; the Evangelist remembers where the ministry took place.\n\nVerse 24 is the chronological anchor: *for John had not yet been thrown into prison.* This is one of the rare points where the Fourth Gospel directly synchronizes with the Synoptic timeline. Matthew 4:12 and Mark 1:14 begin Jesus's Galilean ministry only after John's arrest; John 3:24 fills in the previously-unrecorded period when both ministries overlapped. The detail is offered not as trivia but as setup — the Baptist's coming statement (*He must increase, but I must decrease*) is the position of a forerunner whose work is being eclipsed in real time, before his arrest forced the issue.\n\nThe theological friction surfaces in verses 25-26. A dispute arose between *John's disciples* and *a certain Jew* about *purification* (*katharismos*) — likely a dispute over whose baptism (John's? Jesus's? traditional Jewish?) effected what cleansing. The Baptist's disciples take the question to their teacher, but the way they frame it betrays anxiety, not curiosity: *Rabbi, He who was with you beyond the Jordan, to whom you have testified — behold, He is baptizing, and all are coming to Him* (3:26). The grammar of the complaint is telling. *He who was with you* — He is your apprentice, your handoff. *To whom you have testified* — you vouched for Him, and look what He's doing. *All are coming to Him* — and not to you. The disciples have made the ministry a competition. The Baptist has not.\n\nThe pericope is brief but pastorally pointed. Even faithful disciples can develop tribal loyalty to their teacher that outstrips loyalty to the truth the teacher is testifying about. The Baptist's disciples were better at protecting their rabbi than at receiving his message. The setup is necessary because what comes next (3:27-30) is the Baptist's correction — and the correction is the chapter's hidden imperative.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Diatribo* (3:22) — *spend time*, *linger* — Jesus is not in transit but in extended ministry. *Katharismos* (3:25) — *purification*, *cleansing*; the same root behind the cleansing of the temple (2:14-22) and Ezekiel's promised cleansing water (Ezekiel 36:25). *Paraginomai* (3:23) — *come, arrive*; the imperfect tense pictures continuous flow of people."
